The [DevPortal AI Kit](https://github.com/qed-developerportal/devportal-ai-kit) sample has been created to enable you to start building apps that target publicly available QED APIs with an AI to help you along the way.

The default configuration let’s you get familiar with the APIs via a natural language conversation that you have with an LLM that is installed locally on your device as part of the configuration process.

When you make a request to the LLM, Microsoft’s Semantic Kernel interprets the request and makes API calls to the DevPortal Semantic Kernel Plugin (source code included in the file [DevPortalPlugin.cs](https://github.com/QED-DeveloperPortal/DevPortal-AI-Kit/blob/main/Plugins/DevPortalPlugin.cs)) if it decides that the descriptions that accompany one or more of the Plugin API calls are relevant.

Any responses gathered from calls to the DevPortal Plugin are then sent to the local [LLM](https://llama.meta.com/) (via [Ollama](https://ollama.com)) to be formatted into a final answer that is presented to the user.

In this way you can not only get answers that describe what is available but also code examples of how to use the APIs.
